In the late-1800s, “John Chinaman” became a stock character in political cartoons, usually depicting him as a Chinese laborer. At around this time, the term “Chinaman” took on a pejorative connotation, as politicians and white workers blamed Chinese people for taking their jobs.

Referring to Chinese men as “John” originated from British sailors who, due to the language barrier, could not understand their Chinese counterparts. Census takers in the early and mid-1800s often wrote down names as “John Chinaman,” similar to the modern usage of “John Doe.”

John Chinaman

Nowadays, calling someone a “Chinaman” would probably get you an ugly look (at best). But the term didn’t always have pejorative connotations, at first simply referring to a man from China. https://t.co/2SY3k6VopY
